Part 1: Classification with GMM+Bayes¶

In the previous assignment, we have implemented the GMM model to fit a dataset in a complete unsupervised manner. To recall, given a dataset X={x1,…,xM}X={x1,…,xM} where xi∈RNxi∈RN, the probability density function (pdf) of a KK-component GMM is of the form,

p(x|Θ)=∑k=1Kαkp(x|μk,Σk)p(x|Θ)=∑k=1Kαkp(x|μk,Σk)

where p(x|μk,Σk)p(x|μk,Σk) is the multivariate Gaussian pdf with mean μkμk and covariance ΣkΣk

p(x|μk,Σk)=1(2π)N/2|Σk|1/2exp{−12(x−μk)T(Σk)−1(x−μk)}.p(x|μk,Σk)=1(2π)N/2|Σk|1/2exp⁡{−12(x−μk)T(Σk)−1(x−μk)}.

Θ={θ1,…,θk}Θ={θ1,…,θk} is the complete set of parameters θk={αk,μk,Σk}θk={αk,μk,Σk}, where αkαk are the priors (or mixing weights) of each Gaussian component, satisfying the constraint ∑Kk=1αk=1∑k=1Kαk=1. These parameters are typically learned through the iterative Expectation-Maximization algorithm, which was implemented in the previous assignment.

In this part, we want to decide to which class each datapoint belongs to with models of each class learnt a priori, in other words classification. To perform classification, we need to create a training dataset (i.e. a labeled dataset to build our model) and a testing dataset to evaluate the performance of the algorithm. To perform classification with GMMs, the first step is to learn a GMM for each class from the training set. Given a model for each class, we can use the Gaussian Likelihood Discriminant Rule to classify the testing datapoints.

Gaussian Maximum Likelihood Discriminant Rule¶

A maximum likelihood classifier chooses the class label that is the most likely. For a binary classification problem, a new datapoint x′x′ belongs to class 11 if the corresponding likelihood is superior to the likelihood of class 2,

p(y=1|x′)>p(y=2|x′).p(y=1|x′)>p(y=2|x′).

By Bayes, we have

p(y=i|x′)=p(x′|y=i)p(y=i)p(x′),with class i=1,2.p(y=i|x′)=p(x′|y=i)p(y=i)p(x′),with class i=1,2.

Replacing this term in the Maximum Likelihood (ML) Discriminant Rule for x′x′ in class 11, we obtain

p(x′|y=1)p(y=1)>p(x′|y=2)p(y=2).p(x′|y=1)p(y=1)>p(x′|y=2)p(y=2).

In general, one can assume equal class distribution, i.e. p(y=1)=p(y=2)p(y=1)=p(y=2). By replacing in the previous equation, the discriminant rule becomes

p(x′|y=1)>p(x′|y=2).p(x′|y=1)>p(x′|y=2).

For a GMM composed of KiKi multivariate Gaussian functions, the conditional densities to belong to class ii is similar to the PDF equation,

p(x′|y=i)=∑k=1Kiαkp(x′|μk,Σk),p(x′|y=i)=∑k=1Kiαkp(x′|μk,Σk),

with p(x′|μk,Σk)p(x′|μk,Σk) defined according to PDF equation of the GMM.

In the case of a multi-class problem with i=1...Ii=1...I classes, the ML Discriminant Rule is the minimum of the log-likelihood (i.e., equivalent to maximizing the likelihood). Assuming equal class distribution, the ML Discriminant Rule is:

ci(x′)=argmin{−log(p(x′|y=i))}.ci(x′)=argmin⁡{−log⁡(p(x′|y=i))}.

In the case that one does not make the assumption of equal class distribution, the ML Discriminant Rule is:

ci(x′)=argmin{−log(p(x′|y=i)p(y=i))}.ci(x′)=argmin⁡{−log⁡(p(x′|y=i)p(y=i))}.

Part 2: Resampling from learned GMMs¶

One of the biggest problem of machine learning is the cost of gathering data coupled to the fact that complex ML algorihtms requires a lot of them. The beauty of GMMs is that it is able to learn the underlying structure of a given set of points, which is often refered as density estimation. That is to say, the result of a GMM fit to some data is technically not a clustering model, but a generative probabilistic model describing the distribution of the data. Therefore, one can draw samples from such a probabilistic model, i.e. generate new data points that are not part of the dataset but share its underlying structure. With this, one can create fake data to extand its dataset, or also solve the unbalanced dataset problem by generating more samples of the classes that are missing some.

Drawing samples from a GMM is using the probabilistic model as a random generator. This is a two-steps process. First, one must select which Gaussian kk to draw a sample from based on the prior probabilities αα of the GMM. A Gaussian with a higher prior probability is most likely to be selected. Once a Gaussian is selected, a datapoint is drawn from the multivariate distribution given by the paramater μμ and ΣΣ of the selected Gaussian.

Part 3: Gaussian Mixture Regression (GMR)¶

Regression problems are a category of supervised learning algorithms that seeks to approximate the true mapping function y=f(x)y=f(x) from inputs xx to outputs yy from a set of training data. As opposed to classification, in regression, the output variables are continuous y∈Ry∈R. Such regression problems are found in a wide spectrum of research from financial to robotic applications.

Any regression problem is posed as follows, given a training data set of inputs X={x1,…,xM}X={x1,…,xM} of MM samples, where xi∈RNxi∈RN are NN-dimensional inputs and a set of corresponding outputs y={y1,…,yM}y={y1,…,yM}, where yi∈RPyi∈RP are continuous PP-dimensional outputs, we seek to approximate a continuous mapping function f^:RN→RPf^:RN→RP, y^=f^(x)y^=f^(x), that best recovers the true regressive function y=f(x)y=f(x).

Many linear/non-linear methods exist to obtain this regressive function f(x)f(x). In this assignment we will implement a version using our previously implemented GMMs, Gaussian Mixture Regression. For further reading on these regression methods, refer to the Regression Slides or the lecture Notes from the Applied Machine Learning course.

Gaussian Mixture Regression is a parametric model-based method, capable of learning a regressive function of non-linear datasets. It stems from estimating a joint density of the inputs and outputs through a KK-component Gaussian mixture model as follows:

p(x,y|Θ)=∑k=1Kαkp(x,y|μk,Σk),p(x,y|Θ)=∑k=1Kαkp(x,y|μk,Σk),

where αkαk are the priors of each Gaussian component parametrized by {μk.Σk}{μk.Σk} where

∑k=1Kαk=1,μk=[μkxμky],Σk=[ΣkxxΣkyxΣkxyΣkyy].∑k=1Kαk=1,μk=[μxkμyk],Σk=[ΣxxkΣxykΣyxkΣyyk].

Given this joint density, one can compute the conditional density p(y|x)p(y|x) which will provide our regressive function y=f(x)y=f(x),

p(y|x)=∑k=1Kβkp(y|x;μk,Σk)p(y|x)=∑k=1Kβkp(y|x;μk,Σk)

where

βk=αkp(x|μxk,Σxxk)∑k=1Kαkp(x|μxk,Σxxk).βk=αkp(x|μxk,Σxxk)∑k=1Kαkp(x|μxk,Σxxk).

The βkβk parameters are known as the mixing weights (i.e. relative importance) of each KK-th regressive model p(y|x;μk,Σk)p(y|x;μk,Σk). The regressive function is then obtained by computing the expectation over the conditional density E{p(y|x)}E{p(y|x)} as follows:

y=f(x)=E{p(y|x)}=∑k=1Kβk(x)μ~k(x)y=f(x)=E{p(y|x)}=∑k=1Kβk(x)μ~k(x)

where

μ~k(x)=μky+Σkyx(Σkxx)−1(x−μkx)μ~k(x)=μyk+Σyxk(Σxxk)−1(x−μxk)

are the local regressive functions, which represent a linear function whose slope is determined by ΣkxΣxk (the variance of xx) and ΣkxyΣxyk (the covariance of yy and xx). Our regressive function y=f(x)y=f(x) is thus a linear combination of KK regressive models. The advantage of GMR over other non-linear regressive methods is that we can also compute the uncertainty of the prediction (i.e. the regressed output y^y^) by computing the variance of the conditional function Var{p(y|x)}Var{p(y|x)} as follows:

Var{p(y|x)}=∑i=1Kβk(x)(μ~k(x)2+(Σ~k))−(∑i=1Kβk(x)μ~k(x))2Var{p(y|x)}=∑i=1Kβk(x)(μ~k(x)2+(Σ~k))−(∑i=1Kβk(x)μ~k(x))2

where Σ~kΣ~k represents the variance of the conditional density for each regressive function and is computed as follows:

Σ~k=Σkyy−Σkyx(Σkxx)−1ΣkxyΣ~k=Σyyk−Σyxk(Σxxk)−1Σxyk

Note that Var{p(y|x)}Var{p(y|x)} represents the uncertainty of the prediction NOT of the model. To represent the uncertainty of the model one should compute the likelihood of the joint density; i.e. L(Θ|X,y)=∏i=1M∑k=1Kαkp(x,y|μk,Σk)L(Θ|X,y)=∏i=1M∑k=1Kαkp(x,y|μk,Σk). Another advantage of GMR over most regression methods is that it can be used with multi-dimensional inputs x∈RNx∈RN as well as multi-dimensional outputs y∈RPy∈RP, with the same formulation presented here. For a thorough description of the derivation of this method we recommend reading Hsi Guang Sung's PhD Thesis and Cohn et al's seminal work on learning with statistical models

Step 1: Estimate a Joint Density p(x,y|Θ)p(x,y|Θ) of your Dataset {XX,yy} with a GMM}} The first step in implementing GMR is to learn the joint density of the inputs X∈RM×NX∈RM×N and outputs y∈RM×Py∈RM×P, where NN and PP correspond to the dimensionality of the input and output spaces, respectively. By loading one of the three different 1-D datasets provided in the script tp5_gmmapps_part3.m and selecting the values of KK and cov_type you will fit a GMM to your regression dataset.

Step 2: Compute the Expectation and Variance of the Conditional p(y|x)p(y|x) Once the GMM parameters are estimated for the joint dataset {XX,yy} we can estimate the regressive function by implementing the previously defined equations.

From all of the previous results, it is evident that GMR is a powerful algorithm, capable of modeling regressive functions with different complexities and topologies. For all datasets except 2d-gmm (i.e. 2D highly nonlinear dataset), GMR approximated a regressive function very close to the true one. The example dataset from the latter case is composed of a highly nonlinear output with much noise, for such datasets GMR would give a good estimate if we used as much parameters as possible, for example if we set K=50K=50 this would yield to:

In [26]:
plot_2Dregression(X, y, ftruth, f)

This model provides a fairly better estimate than when K=4K=4, however, the complexity of the model is extremely high (i.e. 340 parameters for a dataset of 500 data-points). For this reason, we must apply a model selection procedure using cross-validation as we do for classification problems.

Note that for such type of datasets, GMR might not be the most suitable algorithm. Other type of local non-parametric methods would be more suitable, such as LWR (Locally Weighted Regression), LWPR (Locally Weighted Projected Regression) or GPR (Gaussian Process Regression). If you are interested in learning about these methods, they are covered in the Advanced Machine Learning Course offered at EPFL during the Spring semesters.

Regression metrics¶

The metric you will use during this practical to compare the performance of each regressor will be the Normalized Mean Square Error (NMSE)Normalized Mean Square Error (NMSE) or the Coefficient of Determination (R2)the Coefficient of Determination (R2). If you have a vector of prediction y^y^ and a vector yy of the observed values corresponding to this prediction, you can compute the Mean Square Error (MSE)Mean Square Error (MSE) of the predictor:

MSE=1M∑i=1M(yi^−yi)2MSE=1M∑i=1M(yi^−yi)2

The Normalized Mean Square Error (NMSE)Normalized Mean Square Error (NMSE) is simply the MSEMSE normalized by the variance of the observed values :

NMSE=MSEVAR(y)=1M∑Mi=1(yi^−yi)21M−1∑Mi=1(yi−μ)2,NMSE=MSEVAR(y)=1M∑i=1M(yi^−yi)21M−1∑i=1M(yi−μ)2,

where μμ is the mean of the observed values : μ=1M∑Mi=1yiμ=1M∑i=1Myi.

The Coefficient of Determination (R2)Coefficient of Determination (R2) is defined as :

R2=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜∑Mi=1(yi−y¯¯¯)(yi^−y^¯¯¯)∑Mi=1(yi−y¯¯¯)2−−−−−−−−−−−−√∑Mi=1(yi^−y^¯¯¯)2−−−−−−−−−−−−−√⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟2=(∑Mi=1(yi−y¯¯¯)(yi^−y^¯¯¯))2∑Mi=1(yi−y¯¯¯)2∑Mi=1(yi^−y^¯¯¯)2R2=(∑i=1M(yi−y¯)(yi^−y^¯)∑i=1M(yi−y¯)2∑i=1M(yi^−y^¯)2)2=(∑i=1M(yi−y¯)(yi^−y^¯))2∑i=1M(yi−y¯)2∑i=1M(yi^−y^¯)2

where y¯¯¯y¯ and y^¯¯¯y^¯ denotes respectively the average of the observed and predicted values of yy.
